PSC way without VPC peering  That is awesome news! Confirming that direct VPC peering works means your core network routing is solid.
Switching over to Private Service Connect (PSC) via a Service Attachment and Endpoint Attachment changes how traffic flows. Instead of using standard routing over peering, Apigee will send traffic through a dedicated, unidirectional endpoint that maps directly to an Internal Load Balancer (ILB) inside your VPC.
To test this path, you have to place your VM behind an Internal Load Balancer first, because you cannot hook a Service Attachment directly to a raw VM.
Here is the exact step-by-step sequence to tear down the old path and set up the PSC architecture.
The PSC Setup Architecture
[ Apigee Runtime ] 
       │ (Southbound Traffic)
       ▼
[ Endpoint Attachment (Apigee side) ]
       │  (Cross-Project Link)
       ▼
[ Service Attachment (Your side) ]
       │
[ Internal HTTP Load Balancer (ILB) ]
       │
[ VM (Nginx) ]
1. Prepare your Backend (VM & ILB)
Before creating the attachments, your VM must be reachable via a standard Google Cloud Internal TCP/UDP Load Balancer or Internal Regional Application Load Balancer.

1

Create an Unmanaged Instance Group
2 min
Go to Compute Engine > Instance groups and create an unmanaged instance group in the same zone as your VM. Add your Nginx VM to this group.
2

Create a PSC Subnet
Required for Service Attachment
Private Service Connect requires a dedicated subnet with a purpose of Private Service Connect to allocate NAT IPs for the incoming Apigee traffic. Create a small subnet (e.g., /28 or /24) in your VPC with this specific purpose.
3
Deploy the Internal Load Balancer (ILB)
5 min
Go to Network Services > Load balancing and create an Internal TCP/UDP Load Balancer (or Regional HTTP ILB):
* Backend: Select the instance group containing your Nginx VM. Set the port to 80.
* Health Check: Create a basic TCP health check on port 80.
* Frontend: Assign it an internal IP from your standard private subnet on port 80.

2. Create the Service Attachment (Your VPC Project)
Now that you have an active ILB, you can expose it to Apigee.
1. Go to Network Services > Private Service Connect.
2. Click the Published Services tab at the top, then click Publish Service.
3. Configure the attachment settings:
    * Load balancer type: Internal passthrough TCP/UDP (or internal application LB depending on what you chose above).
    * Target load balancer: Select your newly created ILB.
    * Connection preference: Choose Accept automatically (easiest for testing) or Accept explicitly if you want to manually approve Apigee's connection request later.
    * NAT subnets: Select the PSC Subnet you created in Step 1.
4. Click Create.
5. Once created, copy the Service attachment URI (it will look like projects/YOUR_PROJECT/regions/YOUR_REGION/serviceAttachments/YOUR_ATTACHMENT_NAME).
3. Create the Endpoint Attachment (Apigee Project)
Because you do not have UI access to the underlying Apigee project infrastructure, you must tell the Apigee API to provision an Endpoint Attachment on its side that points to your Service Attachment URI.
You will use the Apigee UI or an API call to create this link:
1. In the Google Cloud Console, go to Apigee > Admin > Instances.
2. Select your Apigee instance and look for the Endpoint Attachments tab or section.
3. Click Create.
4. Fill in the details:
    * Attachment ID: Give it a clean name (e.g., psc-nginx-backend).
    * Service Attachment: Paste the Service attachment URI you copied at the end of Step 2.
5. Click Create. It will take a couple of minutes for the status to change to Active (or Pending if you chose explicit approval in your backend project).
4. Update and Test Your Apigee Proxy
Once the Endpoint Attachment shows an Active status, Apigee generates a local IP address inside its runtime specifically for that endpoint.
To test it:
1. Go back to your Apigee API Proxy configuration.
2. Edit your Target Endpoint HTTPTargetConnection definition.
3. Change the <URL> tag: Replace your VM's old private IP address with the Endpoint Attachment IP or host generated by Apigee.
4. Deploy the revision and send a test request.
If it returns the Nginx welcome page, you have successfully completed a full loop through a Private Service Connect attachment pipeline!


